Electric consumption forecasting¶

Author Yrieix Leprince
Date April 2018.
Context Work done in order to enter the Craft AI startup.
Dataset http://blog.drhongtao.com/2017/03/gefcom2014-load-forecasting-data.html

The GEFCom2014-E.xlsx contains a dataset that stores 9 years of hourly load (I will suppose in this work that it is a domestic electric consumption record). The dataset also contains 11 years of hourly temperature in Farenheit.

0. Data preprocessing¶

In [4]:
df_E_raw = pd.read_excel(path+'GEFCom2014-E.xlsx')
df_E_raw = df_E_raw.rename(index=str, columns={"T": "temperature"})  # it is dangerous to have a column named T as df.T is a pandas operation
df_E_raw.index = df_E_raw.Date + pd.to_timedelta(df_E_raw.Hour -1, unit='h')
df_E = df_E_raw[['load', 'temperature']]

del df_E_raw # free memory space once the data is preprocessed

1.2 Trends analysis¶

To spot the trend we will use the rolling/moving average method.

The moving average computes for each time point the average value of the points on either side of it. It has the parameter window that corresponds to the number of points to consider for the average computation.

1.2.1 Monthly window¶

In [12]:
window_m = 24 * 30   # 24 hours a day * 30 days a month
In [13]:
ax = df_E.rolling(window_m).mean().plot(secondary_y=['load'], figsize=FIGSIZE, fontsize=FONTSIZE)
ax.set_ylabel('temperature', fontdict=FONT)
ax.right_ax.set_ylabel('load', fontdict=FONT)
plt.title('Monthly Periodicity', fontdict=FONT)
plt.show()

  • As observed on the first glance, both load and temperature records respect some periodicities. Here is spotted the monthly periodicity.

  • On the graph above one can see that temperature seems to have a period twice as long as load.

1.2.2 Yearly window¶

In [14]:
window_y = 24 * 365   # 24 hours a day * 365 days a year
In [15]:
ax = df_E.rolling(window_y).mean().plot(secondary_y=['load'], figsize=FIGSIZE, fontsize=FONTSIZE)
ax.set_ylabel('temperature', fontdict=FONT)
ax.right_ax.set_ylabel('load', fontdict=FONT)
plt.title('Trend over the years', fontdict=FONT)
plt.show()
  • By increasing the size of the rolling window we are able to spot our data's trends over the years.

First order differencing¶

  • In order to remove much of the trends, one can substract spotted periodicity from the value in order to convert it into a stationary timeseries (ie. timeseries whose properties do not depend on the time which the series are observed). Or an other way to proceed is to use a method call differencing. It computes the differences between consecutive observations.

  • "Differencing can help stabilize the mean of a time series by removing changes in the level of a time series, and so eliminating trend and seasonality." https://www.otexts.org/fpp/8/1

In [16]:
df_E.load.diff().plot(figsize=FIGSIZE, fontsize=FONTSIZE)
plt.title('Load', fontdict=FONT)
plt.show()
In [17]:
df_E.temperature.diff().plot(figsize=FIGSIZE, fontsize=FONTSIZE)
plt.title('Temperature °F', fontdict=FONT)
plt.show()
  • One can observe that most of the trends have been eliminated. Here we are looking at the 'noise' of our timeseries.
